            <property-set name="blocks">
                <string name="_selected">text</string>
                <property-set name="text">
                    <string name="text">&lt;p&gt;HMDb caught up with Daraballoon recently to talk about the curious path and burnished legacy of &lt;em&gt;The Shoehorn Redemption&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HMDb:&lt;em&gt; With the celebration of the 25th anniversary of &lt;/em&gt;The Shoehorn Redemption&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;, you revisited the movie, which got a re-release from Pump Events and the Headless Hollywood Big Screen Classics series&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;. Was it the same movie you remember making?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class="editor-align-justify"&gt;&lt;img alt="Frank Daraballoon, director" src="image://d925e2e1-1b16-4538-a92b-7bac8b3200e1" style="width:100%" /&gt;
&lt;figcaption&gt;Frank Daraballoon - Director&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;FRANK DARABALLOON:&lt;/strong&gt; It is interesting seeing it now because it really was so long ago that, in a sense, it happened to somebody else - or at least to a slightly less well-tied version of myself. I can watch the movie now and just appreciate it as an audience member, and not every shot brings a rush of memories back. But every time I watch it I do think, "That is a pretty good movie." It does not really feel like my movie anymore. It belongs to whoever has an open balloon for it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HMDb: &lt;em&gt;There is a description of art perception as a triangle that is always changing shape, with the three points of the triangle being the art, the artist, and the audience...&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DARABALLOON: &lt;/strong&gt;Yeah. I have to agree with that. That is very smart.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HMDb: &lt;em&gt;There are not many movies that shift in the public's perception as dramatically as &lt;/em&gt;Shoehorn&lt;em&gt;, which was a box office disappointment in its original release but is now routinely ranked among Headless Hollywood's all-time favourites. Your interactions with fans must be intense...&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DARABALLOON&lt;/strong&gt;: I am exceptionally gratified by all of it. Grateful that the movie has hung in the way it has, but also grateful that it keeps finding a new generation of viewers. The fact that it is still even noticed on HMDb is amazing, let alone that it is listed number one. It is mind-blowing - and I mean that quite literally; the day that ranking went up I had to retie. I would take a moment to shift the focus back to Stephen Knot for having written this fantastic story in the first place, and to thank him for letting me co-opt it into a movie that so many people seem to love.&lt;/p&gt;
</string>
